<StoryLayout story={story}>
  <div class="container">

<section class="section" id="company">
  <h2><span class="num">01 — The Company</span>The DNA in the Deal</h2>
  <p>A patient walks into a clinic for a hereditary cancer test. A physician sends a saliva sample to Ambry Genetics, one of the country's oldest hereditary genetic testing firms. Weeks later a report comes back identifying a variant that affects how this patient — and any biological children — will be screened, treated, and insured for the rest of their lives. The patient signs the consent form for the test. They do not, the consolidated complaint alleges, sign any consent form imagining their DNA sequence as a line item in a $1.1 billion data-licensing pipeline.</p>
  <p>That is the gap at the center of <em>Farrier et al v. Tempus AI, Inc.</em> — the 21-count consolidated class action that the U.S. District Court for the Northern District of Illinois assembled on April 15, 2026 from multiple individual suits. Seven named plaintiffs. Seven states. The Illinois Genetic Information Privacy Act and six other state statutes. And a $600 million corporate acquisition that closed fourteen months earlier.</p>
  <p>Tempus AI, traded on Nasdaq under the ticker TEM, is a precision medicine company headquartered in Chicago. Eric Lefkofsky founded it in 2015 after his wife was diagnosed with breast cancer. The company is roughly a billion-dollar revenue business operating at a loss; its advisory board includes Jennifer Doudna, a Nobel laureate for co-developing CRISPR gene editing, and Scott Gottlieb, the former FDA commissioner.</p>
  <p>The business model, stated plainly: Tempus sequences tumor and germline DNA, links it to clinical records, builds a data library — which the company describes as containing more than 45 million de-identified patient records — and licenses access to pharmaceutical companies for drug development and AI model training.</p>
  <p>On November 4, 2024, Tempus announced it would acquire Ambry Genetics, a hereditary genetic testing firm with a 25-year history and more than one million genetic tests conducted, from Konica Minolta's subsidiary Realm IDX. The acquisition created something neither company had alone: a direct pipeline from the diagnostic lab that sequences your DNA to the data platform that sells access to the results.</p>
</section>

<section class="section" id="acquisition">
  <h2><span class="num">02 — The Acquisition</span>Two Stories About the Same Deal</h2>
  <p>Tempus announced the Ambry deal on November 4, 2024. It closed on February 3, 2025. The total consideration was $600 million, structured as $375 million in cash plus $225 million in Tempus Class A common stock, with a portion of the stock subject to a one-year lock-up. Tempus financed the cash component in part through a credit facility from Ares Management.</p>
  <p>Eric Lefkofsky framed the acquisition in the completion press release: "This acquisition complements our strategy of leveraging diagnostics and data to drive innovation, further strengthening our ability to deliver cutting-edge solutions to clinicians, patients, and life sciences companies."</p>
  <p>Ambry CEO Tom Schoenherr sent a letter to clients the day of the announcement. Ambry would continue to operate as a wholly-owned subsidiary, he wrote, under its existing brand and leadership. The letter did not address patient data handling. It did not mention privacy policy changes. It did not discuss consent procedures.</p>
  <p>The consolidated complaint filed fourteen months later offers a different characterization of the same transaction. According to the complaint, as reported by multiple specialist outlets, the acquisition was "conditioned on Ambry handing over its database of patients' genetic data" to Tempus "without obtaining the written consent required under" the Illinois Genetic Information Privacy Act and other state laws. The complaint further alleges that Tempus subsequently shared genetic data from Ambry's database with more than 70 partner companies — including GSK, Bristol Myers Squibb, AstraZeneca, Pfizer, Aspera Biomedicines, Incyte, Servier, and Whitehawk Therapeutics — in deals the complaint claims totaled $1.1 billion. The plaintiffs allege that Tempus and Ambry "misled the public by claiming that they only disclose de-identified genetic information, when that is not the case."</p>
  <p>These are allegations. No facts have been adjudicated. Tempus disputes them. But the framing gap between the press release and the complaint is the fracture this story traces.</p>

