<p class="canvas-note"><strong>The Helix</strong> — A rotating double helix of teal particles drifts toward a faint vertical membrane. Each particle dims to gray as it passes through. On the other side, the gray particles reconstitute into the identical helix, teal restored. The membrane accomplished nothing.</p>

<section class="section" id="docket">
  <h2><span class="num">03 — The Docket</span>From Nash to Barone to Farrier</h2>
  <p>The litigation began ten days after Tempus reported its fiscal year 2025 results.</p>
  <p>On February 13, 2026, Jennifer Nash and E.S., a minor, filed <em>Nash et al v. Tempus AI, Inc.</em> (Case No. 1:26-cv-01688) in the U.S. District Court for the Northern District of Illinois. The case was assigned to Judge April M. Perry, with Magistrate Judge Gabriel A. Fuentes. Latham & Watkins represented Tempus. Girard Sharp and Loevy & Loevy represented the plaintiffs.</p>
  <p>Two weeks later, <em>The Cancer Letter</em> published its first analysis. Editor Paul Goldberg noted "two lawsuits filed within days of each other" and drew a distinction that would become central to the litigation: "Deidentified does not equal deidentifiable."</p>
  <p>On March 30, 2026, the case escalated. Lauren Barone, Stephanie Bianco (individually and on behalf of her minor child H.B.), and Eugenia Rukhin filed <em>Barone et al v. Tempus AI, Inc. et al</em> (Case No. 1:26-cv-03516) — an 80-page complaint represented by DiCello Levitt LLP. The Barone complaint named not just Tempus but four AstraZeneca entities as co-defendants: AstraZeneca AB, AstraZeneca LP, AstraZeneca PLC, and AstraZeneca Pharmaceuticals LP. This was a significant expansion. The Nash complaint alleged Tempus collected and shared the data. The Barone complaint alleged that at least one recipient should share liability for receiving it.</p>
  <p>On April 15, 2026, the court consolidated the cases into <em>Farrier et al v. Tempus AI, Inc.</em> — the 21-count complaint that now defines the litigation. The consolidated action names seven plaintiffs from seven states: California, Florida, Georgia, Illinois, Michigan, New York, and West Virginia. It invokes the Illinois Genetic Information Privacy Act along with six other state genetic privacy and consumer protection statutes.</p>

